                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18230409-225-off1199 t18230409-225-cd1200"></join>, a handkerchief, value 2 s., the goods of a person unknown, from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18230409-225-person1977">
                  WILLIAM 
                  JORDAN
               <interp inst="t18230409-225-person1977" type="surname" value="JORDAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18230409-225-person1977" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18230409-225-person1977" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On Sunday evening, the 2d of March, I was in <placeName id="t18230409-225-crimeloc1201">Berwick-street, Soho</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18230409-225-crimeloc1201" type="placeName" value="Berwick-street, Soho"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18230409-225-crimeloc1201" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18230409-225-off1199 t18230409-225-crimeloc1201"></join>, at a fire, I saw the prisoner with three or four others very busy at several gentlemen's pockets - he put his hand into one person's pocket and took out this handkerchief, and put it into his jacket pocket - he joined his companions and shewed it them; they went into the crowd again, and soon after they ran off out of the crowd towards a coffee-shop. I seized him at the door, and charged him with robbing a gentleman of his handkerchief; he said he had none about him - I found it in his pocket. He said he bought it of a boy for 6 d.; then fell on his knees and begged forgiveness. I could not find the owner; he resisted a great deal.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18230409-225-verdict1202" type="verdictDescription">
